Poverty and death in Indonesia&#39;s land of gold
When Bardina Degeiová cooks dinner, she does not use the stove.
In fact, he rarely uses the pan.
In her wooden shack, located in the capital city of Paniai Enarotali in the Indonesian province of Papua, the woman usually simply throws a sweet potato - &quot;nota&quot; in local parlance - directly into the fire.
After half an hour, he takes out the potato and relishes it with unwashed hands.
Bardina sits on the muddy ground - the house is not equipped with furniture - where she also performs her daily chores, such as washing clothes in the cloudy water of a nearby swamp.
A bucket in a room without a roof replaces a toilet.
As the youngest of her husband&#39;s four wives, she was assigned no field to cultivate.
Polygamy is common here.
Working late into the night is dangerous: most of the men in the village are unemployed and often drink alcohol. The village also houses soldiers.
&quot;After five o&#39;clock in the afternoon, no one dares to wander around the village,&quot; says Bardina.
It&#39;s a rare glimpse into daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was declared part of Indonesia in 1969 after a controversial referendum in which just 1,026 elders were forced to vote by public show of hands in front of the occupying army.
A contemporary movement protesting Dutch rule quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which controlled the entire region with the exception of foreign journalists or civil rights watchdogs.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua - independent Papua New Guinea occupied the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is such a remote and desolate town that you can reach after a ninety-minute flight from the provincial capital of Jayapura to Nabire, followed by a stomach-churning five-hour drive.
Public transport does not operate at this location.
The town of 19,000 inhabitants consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, roofs made of wool sheets in shades of gray and rust.
Very few Indonesians, let alone journalists, and virtually no foreigners have looked at this place.
Before the arrival of the Christians, the locals worshiped a god named Uga Tamee.
And that&#39;s not all.
&quot;We weren&#39;t used to wearing these clothes,&quot; says Bardina, pointing to her colorful, hand-woven turban, dark T-shirt and bright skirt.
&quot;We used to carry only leaves.&quot;
Papua is the poorest province of Indonesia - 28% of the population lives below the poverty line, and the child mortality and literacy rate here is one of the worst in Asia.
At the same time, however, it is Indonesia&#39;s land of gold.
The largest and most profitable Grasberg gold mine in the world, owned by Freeport McMoran of Phoeenix, USA, is located only 60 miles from Paniai - a rocky province about the size of New Jersey, home to about 153,000 inhabitants.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper here.
In addition, Papua supports an estimated $78 billion worth of logging.
However, these riches are a source of suffering for Papuans and a guarantee of oppression by the powerful Indonesian military.
A 2005 New York Times investigation found that Freeport paid local military officials and units about $20 million between 1998 and 2004, including $150,000 for one officer.
Papuans calling for self-government threaten this golden goose and are therefore severely suppressed.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed and thousands more raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military since 1969.
Mass killings in the tribal region of Papua during the 1970s amounted to genocide, according to the Asian Human Rights Commission.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
We Will Lose Everything, a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, describes atrocities that took place last year, such as extrajudicial killings, torture - according to another report, rape and electrocution are particularly popular - and the brutal crackdown on peaceful protesters.
&quot;It&#39;s difficult to count the number of victims because incidents happen every week,&quot; said Andreas Harsono, Indonesia researcher for Human Rights Watch.
The whole situation was aggravated by the fact that Papuan resources were attracting colonists to Indonesia.
Of the province&#39;s 3.5 million inhabitants, 83% profess Christianity, but the demographics are changing with the influx of Muslim immigrants from the Indonesian islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese canteens sell fried chicken and gado-gado, or mixed vegetables with peanut sauce.
Local people are fighting for survival.
&quot;Immigrants started selling chicken and vegetables in traditional markets at lower prices than local Papuans,&quot; explains 24-year-old Abeth You, who was born in Pania and moved to the provincial capital Jayapura for work.
&quot;The original inhabitants of Papua - the mama-mama (women) - thus lost their jobs.&quot;
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, nicknamed Jokowi, promised to tackle inequality and rights abuses during his 2014 presidential campaign.
The former carpenter secured 27 of Papua&#39;s 29 districts, including Paniai, on his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta.
But very little has changed in Papua, and local people feel betrayed.
“Our hearts are broken because we voted for Jokpwi in 2014 with the hope that he would hear our call for justice,” You said.
The fact is that just two months after Jakowi&#39;s inauguration in October, Paniai experienced a big shock.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were singing Christmas carols by a campfire in the town of Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on motorbikes emerged from the darkness of the night.
Two of the surprised children told them they should turn on the lights.
One of the soldiers was touched by the rebuke and the tone in which it was delivered and later returned with four other soldiers, local priest Yavedt Tebai said.
Two of the soldiers, in a drunken state, chased a group of children and beat them with the butts of their weapons, victims and witnesses said.
One of the soldiers then fired at a group of children.
One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to a nearby election commission building, and things escalated the next day.
About 1,000 young Papuan men and women gathered on a soccer field in front of the local police station and army headquarters, demanding justice.
They came with ceremonial hunting bows and performed the waita dance - which involves running in a circle and imitating birdsong - of the Papuan Mee Pago tribe.
A few protestors started throwing stones at the buildings.
With tensions mounting, soldiers were ordered over the radio: &quot;If the crowd tries to resist at least three times, you are authorized to shoot,&quot; read an official document, the contents of which have never been released to local media, according to TIME.
Yeremias Kayame (56), head of the Enarotali Kego Koto district, recognized the impending danger and urged residents to disperse to their homes.
However, no one heeded his words.
&quot;When I turned around, someone shot me in the left wrist,&quot; he told TIME on the porch of his colorfully painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn&#39;t know who the shooter was, but according to him, the bullet belonged to one of the soldiers present.
&quot;There were a lot of people around and a lot of shooting,&quot; he added.
One of the local residents, Alfius Youw, was hit three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
&quot;I ran to the body to make sure it was really him,&quot; Yohanes, who like many Indonesians uses only one name, told TIME weekly in a somber voice.
&quot;I saw he was dead... I kissed him.&quot;
Papua&#39;s Inspector General of Police, General Yotje Mende, told reporters that his officers were only &quot;securing&quot; the station that was under attack.
&quot;We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us,&quot; Papuan police spokesman Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo said in 2015.
&quot;It&#39;s a matter of life and death.&quot;
According to Human Rights Watch, five protesters were killed and many escaped injury.
The news of the murders made headlines in the Jakarta media the following day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave an impassioned speech in Jayapura, expressing his sympathy for the victims&#39; families and promising to address the violence in Papua.
&quot;I demand an immediate solution to this problem so that it can never happen again,&quot; he said.
National Security Minister Wiranto announced in October 2016 that he would establish an extrajudicial mechanism to resolve past acts of violence.
Almost immediately, however, excuses began to be heard.
“Most of the violent acts happened a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the 90s of the last century and some at the beginning of the 21st century.
What I mean by that is that we are determined to punish these acts of violence, but it will not be an easy task,” he said.
However, in a June 5 interview with TIME magazine held in Jakarta, Wiranto claimed that he had no plans to introduce any measures in Papua.
Instead, he said &quot;all cases will be brought to trial.&quot;
Wiranto - who has been accused by the UN of &quot;crimes against humanity&quot; following more than one thousand deaths during East Timor&#39;s 1999 independence elections - said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua, including the Paniai incident, had been settled so far.
The families of the Paniai shooting victims greeted his claims with disbelief.
&quot;I have been interviewed a total of four times in the last three years, but so far I have not received anything,&quot; said Yohanes.
&quot;I am tired.&quot;
Years later, he says, he still lives in fear.
&quot;I&#39;m afraid,&quot; as he himself claims.
&quot;I&#39;m afraid the army will arrest me or someone will shoot me.&quot;
His brother Yacobus confirmed the view of many residents of Paniai who are afraid to talk about the incident.
According to him, he was beaten by members of the army after helping to bury four of the victims.
&quot;After the bodies were buried, the army started looking for me,&quot; he said.
And the shooting still doesn&#39;t stop.
