China lacks tourists.
Beijing loses billions due to visa policy.
For decades, China has sought to exert its influence without the use of force.
It spends ten billion dollars a year supporting language schools and building universities abroad, pushing its entertainment industry into foreign markets and trying to attract Western tourists.
But Beijing is not doing well.
The state media there talk about a plan to make tourism the driving force of economic transformation and modernization.
However, the number of arrivals increased by only 3.8 percent last year, and roughly 80 percent of tourists to China came from Hong Kong, Macau and Taiwan.
This is caused, among other things, by the fact that, despite all its global aspirations, China does not exactly welcome foreigners with open arms, assesses the situation in the world&#39;s most populous country, Christopher Balding, a professor of economics from Peking University, in an article for the Bloomberg agency.
An example that speaks for itself is China&#39;s visa policy.
Only 13 countries have visa-free relations with China, citizens of the others must arrange a visa in advance.
Therefore, the crowds at Chinese offices in the US are comparable to Chinese New Year celebrations.
The visa costs $140, but if you don&#39;t want to wait in line for long hours, you have to pay $100 or more for additional services.
Such restrictions create significant economic barriers.
A study by the Journal of Economics and Finance showed that the need for a visa reduces the number of visitors to a given country by 70 percent.
In 2015, just two million Americans visited mainland China, while Hong Kong, which accounts for less than three percent of China&#39;s gross domestic product and is home to less than one percent of the total population, had 1.8 million Americans.
China often exacerbates this problem itself when it uses tourism to realize its political goals, for example in disputes with Taiwan and South Korea.
When China restricted shipping to South Korea in the spring amid a rift over South Korea&#39;s anti-missile system, the South Koreans retaliated by shunning China.
Visits fell 42 percent year-on-year in May, while Japan saw an 85 percent increase.
All this affects macroeconomic stability.
According to a recently published report by the US Federal Reserve Bank, as much as $190 billion may have left China as a result of Chinese foreign travel, while China receives about $35 billion a year from selling foreign currency to inbound tourists.
According to official figures on the development of the balance of payments, China had a deficit of 217 billion dollars in tourism last year, which is equal to 44 percent of the entire Chinese surplus in trade in goods.
A small number of tourists therefore deals a very painful blow to a country that is anxiously preventing the outflow of capital.
However, the above-mentioned factors are only one manifestation of a more general reticence towards foreigners.
In many parts of China, practically no one has heard of immigrants.
As recently as 2013, there were less than a million foreigners living in all of China.
Even some individual cities in the United States have more of them.
Even Japan, which is not exactly a crossroads of immigration, has twice as many.
At the same time, a number of scientific works show that immigrants usually stimulate economic growth, entrepreneurship and innovation.
However, you will not find them in China.
Solving these problems will be politically difficult, but a step that is being offered is to simplify the visa apparatus.
Other Asian countries, especially India and Vietnam, have recently made great efforts to simplify and lower the cost of visa procedures.
If China wants more foreign tourists and their hard currency, it should be easier for them to get there.
