Burma and Senegal.
Where can Czechs vote?
In the autumn parliamentary elections, registered voters will be able to vote for the composition of the House of Representatives from Burma, Senegal or Luxembourg.
In these and several other countries, the Czech Republic has opened embassies since the last parliamentary elections in 2013.
This follows from the decree that regulates the delivery of ballot papers abroad.
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs has prepared its update, it is currently in the comments procedure.
Four years ago, 10,000 Czech citizens voted for MPs abroad.
&quot;Since the last amendment of the decree in 2013, there have been some changes that must be taken into account in these lists,&quot; the ministry explains its procedure.
&quot;In some countries, new embassies were established, some offices were closed, or there was a change in the level of representation,&quot; the material reads.
The decree contains two appendices, the first of which lists the embassies to which paper ballots are delivered.
This group of offices includes the representation of the Czech Republic in neighboring countries, i.e. Germany, Poland, Austria and Slovakia.
More than a hundred other Czech authorities will receive a ballot in a printable version.
It is their list that is changed by the decree.
Four years ago, Czechs could vote, for example, at the Czech embassy in Libya or Zimbabwe.
Both embassies are closed today.
The Czech Republic also canceled its representation in Bamako, Malaysia, and Kyoto, Japan.
There will be no elections at the Consulate General in Donetsk either.
The Czech Republic closed it in 2014 due to the war in eastern Ukraine.
Embassies in Kenya&#39;s Nairobi, Senegal&#39;s capital Dakar and Zambia&#39;s Lusaka are newly on the list.
In Asia, since the last parliamentary elections, the Czech Republic has expanded its representation with a consulate general in Irbil, Iraq, and Chengdu, the capital of the Chinese province of Sichuan.
Ballots will also be available for registered voters at the Czech embassies in Burma and Cambodia.
Czechs abroad have had the opportunity to choose deputies in polling stations at embassies or consulates four times so far.
Before each election, the state election commission determines by lot the region whose candidates are voted for abroad.
The first time was in 2002, when a decision was made between South Moravian candidates.
In the following two elections, Czechs abroad voted for South Bohemian candidates.
In 2013, as this year, the Central Bohemian region was selected.
The number of Czechs voting abroad is steadily increasing.
At the premiere 15 years ago, roughly 3,800 people came to vote, in 2006 there were around 6,700, and four years later 8,222.
For early parliamentary elections four years ago, 10,571 voters came to the embassies.
Moore&#39;s Ford Bridge massacre: activists recall racist lynching
A 1948 Ford Mercury zoomed past the onlookers of Monroe, Georgia and careened toward the Moore&#39;s Ford Bridge.
However, before the car with four black passengers and a white driver could reach the bridge, a group of white men with guns blocked its path.
The leader of the group - a middle-aged man in a striped suit - took a long drag on his cigarette and stared at the windshield of the car.
Inside, the passengers were shaking with fear.
&quot;We want the f---ing Roger!&quot; the man yelled.
&quot;Bring him to me!&quot;
The silence is broken by the roar of a young black man being pulled from the passenger seat.
Fortunately, this scene is merely a reconstruction of the events that took place on July 22nd.
But when one of the men throws a noose over &quot;Roger&#39;s&quot; neck, the audience gasps in excitement.
Since 2005, a group of activists have been returning to Moore&#39;s Ford Bridge regularly to reenact that fateful night in 1946, when two black couples - Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and Mae Murra Dorsey - were killed by members of the Ku Klux Klan.
No one has yet been tried for the murders.
“It&#39;s a wonder that not one person has been arrested in all these years - even though we still see them in our community; even though we know their identity,&quot; said Tyrone Brooks, who is helping to organize the reenactment of the event.
&quot;It is a stain on our history and a burden on our souls.&quot;
Brooks is a 71-year-old former Georgia congressman and lifelong civil rights activist.
In his eyes, the reconstruction of the event represents a dramatic call to action. Every year, the community of Monroe is reminded that justice has not been done enough.
&quot;We want prosecution and closure, we want peace of mind and reconciliation, but above all justice,&quot; Brooks said.
&quot;Until then, the process of healing and reconciliation cannot begin.&quot;
A medical examiner covers one of the bodies of a lynching victim at Moore&#39;s Ford on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, up to 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were said to have participated in the lynching.
However, no one has yet been prosecuted.
Despite the fact that the suspects remain at large for decades, civil rights advocates say that both reasons for the lynching - politics and sex - were known to everyone in the city.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court decision gave black residents of Georgia the right to participate in elections scheduled for the summer for the first time.
And just during the summer election, according to the FBI, black farmer Roger Malcom was supposed to stab white landowner Barnett Hester during a fight - allegedly because of his wife.
According to Brooks, the town&#39;s tradition was that Hester had intercourse with Malcom&#39;s wife, Dorothy, and brought her into a different state.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, prominent white landowner Loy Harrison posted a $600 bond for Malcom.
He was accompanied to the prison by Dorothy and cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
On their way back from the prison, just before the entrance to Moore&#39;s Ford bridge, a group of suspects blocked their way.
&quot;As it turned out, the murders were planned and orchestrated by Harrison,&quot; the FBI concluded.
&quot;It is also clear that there was collusion between state and local law enforcement officers who not only participated in the lynching, but also disposed of evidence and concealed the identities of witnesses.&quot;
Brooks was more succinct on the matter.
&quot;It was a suffrage massacre,&quot; he said.
&quot;The murders had a clear subtext for all local black residents: &#39;this is what you will do if you register and vote&#39;.&quot;
The annual reenactment of the Moore&#39;s Ford Bridge event has been organized by Cassandra Greene for nearly a decade.
Her presentation is imaginative, engaging and concise. It shows the deep-seated racism that many would like to see as extinct in modern America.
This reconstruction isn&#39;t easy to watch, and it&#39;s even harder to look away, but Greene says there&#39;s a point.
&quot;No one wants to talk about lynching because we have to face the uncomfortable feelings that are hidden inside each of us,&quot; Greene said.
&quot;However, there can be no relationship between us unless you hear what I have had to go through.&quot;
The main rehearsals for this year&#39;s reconstruction began in June, and on the very first day, approximately 30 actors - a dozen white, the rest black - crowded into the room, where Greene introduced them to a very carefully planned performance.
Wade Marbaugh serves as assistant director.
For many years he played the leader of the Ku Klux Klan, but according to him, the role is exhausting.
&quot;I feel bad about it because it goes against who I am,&quot; Marbaugh said.
&quot;I think it&#39;s very important to remember this part of history regularly because we never want to go back to that time.&quot;
Actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, who play the role of Roger Malcom, thus Barnett Hester, rehearse their roles.
The play begins with a scuffle - Malcom argues with Hester and accuses him of sleeping with his wife.
&quot;Get the n---e off my property!&quot;
You can&#39;t do Rascon.
A scuffle ensues.
At that moment, everyone (at least every black actor) bursts out laughing.
Greene laughs the most.
&quot;What happened?&quot; Rascona asks.
He is confused.
Was I too rude?
&quot;No,&quot; Greene replies cheerfully.
&quot;I just don&#39;t think white people said &#39;n--r&#39; in that tone back then.&quot;
&quot;Exactly,&quot; blurts out one of the black actors.
&quot;You need to put more emphasis on R.&quot;
The energy in the room is suddenly better; enmity will be replaced by a feeling of rapprochement.
Everyone wants the show to be authentic. If only to make up for the four victims of the massacre.
The actors repeat the scene.
This time, Rascona emphasizes the correct pronunciation of the N word.
Nobody&#39;s laughing now.
The show ends violently and quickly.
Roars, gunshots... and silence.
A woman dressed in black stands over the actors&#39; bodies and sings Billie Holiday&#39;s mournful song &quot;Strange Fruit&quot;.
There is sadness in the room with every word.
In the background of it all, about a dozen onlookers wipe sweat and tears from their eyes.
There are practically equal numbers of blacks and whites in the audience.
One couple traveled all the way from Ithaca, New York, many onlookers are from nearby.
Each of them endures the humid local climate for almost eight hours, and Brooks leads them in a crowd to the graves of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Up until this point, the murders might have been viewed with distance, but now, standing in the same spot where the lynching took place, the atmosphere is eerie.
With the last words of the song, Greene invites the crowd of onlookers to inspect the bodies.
Children kneel by the victims&#39; heads, watch the fake blood and motionless bodies, and whisper something in each other&#39;s ear.
&quot;They&#39;re not dead,&quot; the little boy snaps.
A few minutes pass and Greene thanks the audience. It&#39;s end.
The actors clean up the rope and wipe away their tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbaugh, a man in a suit who played the leader of the Ku Klux Klan.
Nick Rascona hugs his two actor friends and cries in their arms; eventually his emotions get the better of him.
&quot;It&#39;s okay,&quot; one of the women whispers.
&quot;We know that the role is against you.
But you had a reason for it.&#39;
Later that day, the audience joins the cast for dinner.
At one table, a young white couple is talking passionately about an introduction to a black couple they met today.
Denise Duplinski could hardly find words to express how she felt about tonight&#39;s performance.
&quot;It&#39;s difficult to listen to those ugly words and watch those heinous acts ... committed by people who look like you and do it because they look like you,&quot; she said of the reconstruction.
&quot;It makes me realize that lynching is still a hot topic,&quot; she added, &quot;but it&#39;s called a police shootout.&quot;
Across the room, Tyrone Brooks sits in a courtroom. He enjoys his dinner while talking about civil rights.
According to his own words, he has already started planning performances for next year.
&quot;The reconstruction of these events is inspiring because it describes the fear we had to live through - but it&#39;s also a moment for reflection,&quot; he said.
“If we don&#39;t learn from this, who knows... it could happen again.
People who do not know and do not study the history of their country are condemned to repeat it.&quot;
