The latest test results to determine the age limit for asylum applications in Sweden
The latest test results of asylum seekers in Sweden who were subjected to a new method of assessing their age show that over 80 percent of people were questioned as over 18, but not everyone believes their accuracy.
The Swedish Forensic Medicine Agency (RÃ¤ttsmedicinalverket) started carrying out the new tests at the beginning of this year.
The goal of the method is a more accurate assessment of applicants within the framework of the evaluation of asylum applications. The measure was taken after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for failing to determine the correct age of some refugees who had lied about their age.
To date, the Swedish Migration Agency has referred 6,880 cases for investigation and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests carried out between mid-March and 31 July 2017.
80 percent (2002) were judged to be over the age of 18, while in a further 25 cases the Forensic Medicine Agency judged the interviewee to be &quot;possibly over 18&quot;.
In another 423 cases, the interviewee was determined to be &quot;possibly under 18 years of age.&quot;
The tests are only used if the age of the interviewee is questionable.
