&quot;Compared to last month, the statistics are flat and the numbers are very similar,&quot; he told The Local.
The higher number of applicants whose age was estimated to be older than 18 does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers are lying about their age.
In May, the agency released the results of 581 tests and said that in 442 cases &quot;the subject was found to be 18 years of age or older.&quot;
The newspaper Svenska Dagbladet investigated 581 published cases and found that in 243 cases the interviewee stated that he would be 18 years old this year.
The medical method of determining age, which includes an X-ray of the wisdom teeth and an MRI scan of the knee joints, which are then assessed by dentists and radiologists, has also received criticism.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus from the Karolinska Institute, which, among other things, deals with assessing the biological maturity of people to determine the age when the person in question went through puberty.
“I&#39;ve had reason to think about this issue and I don&#39;t think these types of measurements to judge age are correct.
Judging biological age is, in a sense, very uncertain.
If we cannot determine the age with precision, we should not pretend otherwise,&quot; he told the Metro newspaper.
The Agency&#39;s Forensic Medicine Agency&#39;s GÃ¶ransson defended the decision, saying: &quot;In general, the risk of misjudging a child as an adult is small.
The highest risk is represented by the fact that the person interviewed is just under the age of 18, which in this case corresponds to 10 percent of all interviewees.&quot;
