How football&#39;s financial rules will affect Neymar&#39;s move to Paris
Rules limiting the funding of European football clubs will not in any way affect Neymar&#39;s record transfer from Spain&#39;s Barcelona to France&#39;s Paris-Saint Germain.
Any penalty for Paris Saint-Germain will be implemented by EUFA, which oversees European football teams and has the power to ban teams from the prestigious Champions League.
Financial fair play (FFP) rules, introduced by UEFA in 2011, state that PSG will have to prove that Neymar&#39;s transfer was not financed without major losses.
Barcelona paid the equivalent of €222 million just to buy Neymar out of his contract and Neymar will demand a salary of several tens of millions of dollars a year.
The following are several financial terms of Neymar&#39;s transfer to France.
Since the PSG team is funded by a wealthy Qatari family who made their fortune selling energy, they can afford to bring Neymar into an already stellar football family.
Clubs can spend huge sums to buy players, but on the other hand, they have to demonstrate legitimate sources of income, which allows them to cover the overhead costs of football-related business activities.
FFP was introduced by Michel Platini after taking over as UEFA director in 2007.
The former France player believed that clubs who take on debt in the pursuit of new signings are ultimately cheating and risking bankruptcy if banks or owners refuse to bail them out.
In 2011, FFP rules shifted their focus from club debts to monitoring their losses.
This change meant that the business model used by Roman Abramovich with Chelsea in 2003 - buy a club with potential and spend huge sums on players and build a global brand - was suddenly not so profitable.
Under the current three-year trial period, which ends in 2018, clubs can report a loss of up to €30 million.
And despite the fact that Platini had to leave his post in 2015, his successor Aleksander Čeferin is determined to defend the ban on excessive spending.
&quot;FFP rules are still in place and we are committed to strengthening them in the future,&quot; Andrea Traverso, who oversees FFP compliance, told the Associated Press last week.
Although PSG paid the amount for the buyout of Neymar in a single payment, for accounting purposes they can spread the amount over the entire duration of the contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year deal, so the transfer can be broken down to €44.4 million annually over five years.
The first wave of FFP&#39;s top sanctions hit PSG in 2014 along with Manchester City, which is owned by the Abu Dhabi group.
PSG were fined €60 million ($82 million) - which was later reduced to €20 million - and ordered to reduce their Champions League squad to 21 players for the 2014-2015 season, instead of 25 players.
UEFA is wary of teams who may try to circumvent financial regulators by increasing their income through companies linked to club owners.
So even if a Qatari company sponsors PSG, once the funding exceeds the value of the standard market rate, UEFA has the right to prohibit the amount from being billed.
UEFA took similar action in 2014 after deciding that the amount of funding provided by the Qatar Tourism Authority to PSG was too high.
Part of Neymar&#39;s income at PSG could be reimbursed by the organizing committee of the 2022 FIFA World Cup in Qatar, according to some reports.
However, PSG and Qatar 2022 World Cup officials denied that Neymat should become a World Cup ambassador and that such a maneuver would be easily detected by UEFA officials.
The previous sanctions imposed on PSG mean UEFA will be keeping a close eye on any attempt to circumvent the rules,
According to an insider&#39;s statement on Tuesday, UEFA has not opened any investigation into Neymar&#39;s transfer to PSG.
The source of this report wished to remain anonymous as he is not authorized to comment on the situation with PSG, The Associated Press reported.
The latest published accounts show that PSG closed 2015-2016 with a net profit of €10 million and a turnover of €542.4 million.
The financial statements for the current financial year have not yet been published.
