The club promises to increase turnover by up to 30 percent from the signing of the contract.
Spanish league officials, clearly concerned about the departure of one of their biggest stars, sought to thwart Neymar&#39;s departure, arguing that PSG would breach FFP rules.
&quot;It is a clear case of &#39;financial doping&#39; of the club and the state,&quot; La Liga president Javier Teba told Spanish newspaper AS, referring to PSG&#39;s ownership by a Qatari syndicate.
Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by an American sports tycoon, shares La Liga&#39;s same stance on club funding.
&quot;It is the result of ownership that has fundamentally changed the world of football in the last 15 years,&quot; Wenger was quoted as saying on Thursday.
&quot;Once the state becomes the owner of the club, everything is possible.
Compliance with the rules of financial fair play is very difficult because the state may have different interests in the participation of such players in its club.
