The entrepreneur has to serve ten years for extreme tax evasion.
The Constitutional Court rejected the complaint of businessman Jiří Toman, who has to serve ten years in prison for tax evasion to a considerable extent.
The calculated damage amounts to 645 million crowns.
In the complaint, Toman claimed that the judiciary violated his basic rights, and the factual findings of the courts in Zlín and Olomouc are said to be incomplete.
However, the constitutional judges called the complaint unfounded, ČTK found out from the court&#39;s database.
The Supreme Court is not another court of appeal.
&quot;As a fourth instance, it cannot assess factual or legal errors allegedly committed by general courts, if they do not represent a violation of constitutionally protected rights and freedoms,&quot; the resolution states.
Toman was tried as a fugitive.
The verdict has been valid since November 2015, when it was confirmed by the High Court in Olomouc.
At that time, Toman was in extradition custody in Argentina, where, according to the resolution, he was also at the time of the Ús decision.
The imposed penalty is at the upper limit of the legal rate, which, according to the verdict, corresponds to the damage caused.
The Supreme Court described the case as extreme tax evasion, which has a macroeconomic impact on the state budget.
From 2005 to 2008, the man was the chairman of the board of directors of World Servis.
Damage of 645 million crowns was incurred only in the period from January to July 2008, the total leak, according to the expert, exceeded one billion.
However, due to procedural reasons, it was no longer possible to sue Toman for the entire amount.
According to the indictment, World Servis failed to include all invoices in its tax returns.
Instead of monthly VAT and consumption taxes in the order of at least tens of millions of crowns, taxes were paid in just hundreds of thousands.
World Servis as well as some of the companies with which the company did business are related to businessman Radomír Vybíral, who was sentenced to 13 years in prison for VAT machinations in the fuel business.
His complaint was also rejected some time ago by the Constitutional Court.
The series &quot;The Summer of Not Surviving&quot; and &quot;Comrade Detective&quot; strike a nostalgic chord
This iteration of the story is nostalgic for both the characters from the glorious 80s; so for the sleazy 90s (when geniuses David Wain and Michael Showalter launched the MTV sketch comedy &quot;The State&quot;); and, of course, for modern times, namely 2001, before stars like Elizabeth Banks, Amy Poehler and Paul Rudd fled to bigger projects.
As a cultural artifact, it is both a light parody and an embodiment of our modern Facebook era of lasting memories.
But from the perspective of the franchise, it looks like someone is running out of breath.
The series &quot;First Day of Camp&quot; worked surprisingly well - not only because of the absurd humor (an example can be the story of the creation of a talking vegetable can, narrated by H. Jon Benjamin).
The authors deviated from the main funny point - middle-aged actors playing teenage horny children - and could not draw from previous events.
The sequel &quot;Ten Years Later&quot;, in which adults play adults, does not push as much on the emotional level, and the satire is sporadic at times, including a parody of 90&#39;s thrillers like &quot;The Hand in the Cradle&quot;.
At one point, a character finds an Apple Powerbook, roller skates and &quot;a lot of other stuff from 1991&quot; in a pile of junk.
Many of the main story lines are repeated.
Good-hearted Coop (Mr. Showalter), now a writer, still hasn&#39;t gotten over his love for Katie (Marguerite Moreau).
Victor (Ken Marino) is still a freak.
Not to mention the crazy plot involving Ronald Reagan (also Mr. Showalter) being egged on by George HW Bush (a very well cast Michael Ian Black).
As always, the best part of the franchise is the many side stories.
Especially fun to watch is the eternally young, long-haired Rudd, aka Matt Dillon&#39;s character from The Youth, whose once-respectable character Andy is now an old-timer.
The franchise could be kicked off by moments of random insanity, like the more recurring &quot;Seven Up&quot; series, until it reaches what I assume will be its logical denouement: &quot;Wet Hot American Summer: Twenty Years Later,&quot; when the final scene sees the whole group go on a the premiere of &quot;The Years of Not Surviving&quot;.
Amazon&#39;s &quot;Comrade Detective,&quot; meanwhile, appeals to a different kind of nostalgia: the Cold War revival of &quot;Such Normal Americans,&quot; &quot;Atomic Blonde: No Remorse&quot; and even &quot;GLOW,&quot; a show that pits Eastern and Western wrestling icons against each other.
The comedy from creators Brian Gatewood and Alessandro Tanaka, directed by Rhys Thomas, is meant to work as a TV production: a drama about two Bucharest policemen in 1980s Romania who fight for truth and atheism in the Marxist-Leninist way.
The main roles - tenacious Gregor and idealistic Iosef - are played by Florin Piersic Jr. and Cornelia Street, dubbed into English by Channing Tatum (executive producer of the series) and Joseph Gordon-Levitt.
It&#39;s a wonderful idea.
Unfortunately, it&#39;s not much more than that.
Some of the jokes will make you laugh (like the policemen watching chess on TV - a parody of American football).
Many well-known actors lent their voices to the series - including Jenny Slate, Nick Offerman, Mahershala Ali and Chloë Sevigny.
But &quot;Comrade Detective&quot; focuses too much on the inept propaganda drama - which also includes a Reagan-masked assassin - and it looks like it.
Six long episodes are too wordy and there are not enough comedic moments.
With a shorter footage, the propaganda satire in &quot;Comrade Detective&quot; could work, such as in the scene where Gregor and Iosef repeatedly visit the US Embassy, in the lobby of which two fat men are devouring hamburgers stacked in a large pile.
A clear message for the imaginary communist audience is the fact that Western culture can turn everything into a feast and an orgy.
The fictional Romanian creators were not wrong: we do so with our own culture as well as theirs.
The Russian athletes did not live to see the lifting of the IAAF ban.
At the congress in London, the International Athletics Federation IAAF confirmed the extension of the international ban on the starts of Russian athletes due to the state-supported doping program.
As expected, the voting at the venue of the world championship, which starts on Friday, was very clear.
166 delegates spoke in favor of extending the ban, with only 21 votes against.
The main reason for the rejection is primarily the fact that Russia fails to meet all the requirements for the introduction of an anti-doping system, as the head of the IAAF special investigation group Rune Andersen stated before the congress.
His group recommended that the ban continue.
Some older doping cases remain unsolved, a number of suspected athletes have yet to be heard and coaches with tarnished reputations are still working in the country.
Even the Russian Anti-Doping Agency RUSADA is not yet fully functional, as it does not meet the standards of the World Anti-Doping Agency.
However, RUSADA can now conduct testing under the supervision of foreign experts and the British Anti-Doping Agency.
&quot;While progress has been made, there is still much work to be done,&quot; said IAAF President Sebastian Coe.
The Russian Athletics Federation was suspended in November 2015, so Russian athletes lost, among other things, last year&#39;s Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro.
Despite the ban, 19 Russians will participate in the upcoming WC, having already proven that they were tested outside the Russian anti-doping system for a long time.
However, they will not be able to start in the national colors at the championship, and in case of victory, they will not play the Russian national anthem.
Bank of England keeps interest rate at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to announce that interest rates will remain unchanged, following lackluster economic growth and weaker inflation that has dampened speculation of a sharp rise.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will continue to remain &quot;in the background&quot; in relation to keeping interest rates - despite the squeeze on household budgets.
Policymakers at the Bank of England&#39;s Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted six to two to keep interest rates at 0.25%. The results of the interest rate hike vote supported lackluster economic growth supported by weak growth.
In its annual inflation report, the bank forecast growth of 1.7% in 2017 and 1.6% in 2018 and warned that household budget cuts would continue. The bank expects inflation to rise to 3% in the fall.
At the same time, the bank indicated that there should be growth over the next few years as a result of inflation caused by Brexit, and also said that property rents should rise more than expected in financial markets.
Committee members also voted to withdraw part of a mammoth stimulus package put in place a year ago in response to Brexit.
As a result of the above, the Term Funding Plan, which will offer cheap subsidies to banks, is due to come into force from next February, although the Bank of England has said it will now offer £15bn less than the planned £115bn.
Just before the decision, the bank said: &quot;The MPC forecasts that gross domestic product (GDP) will stagnate in the short term, with pressure on real household incomes and a burden on consumption.&quot;
On the subject of rates, the bank said it would need to &quot;tighten monetary policy&quot; to calm inflation, &quot;to a greater extent&quot; than markets expect.
Markets are currently predicting the first increase in the third quarter of next year and another increase in 2020.
However, the bank stressed that any increase would be &quot;gradual&quot; and &quot;limited&quot;.
The bank cut its growth forecast for this year and next year, compared to 1.9% and 1.7% forecast in May.
Expected growth in 2018 at 1.8% remained unchanged.
The pound fell against the dollar and euro after the estimates were released.
The pound fell by 0.5% to 1.31 dollars and by 0.4% to 1.11 euros.
The decision to maintain the status quo came after a disappointing increase buried hopes for further growth - GDP stalled at 0.3% in the second quarter, down from 0.2% in the previous three months.
The increase will most likely remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, although it should increase slightly towards the end of the year, according to the bank.
The latest inflation report comes as little comfort to households hit by soaring inflation and paltry pay rises. The bank said the situation would get worse before the increase.
The report went on to say that monetary policy &quot;cannot prevent&quot; incomes from falling in the coming years, but wages are expected to rise &quot;significantly&quot; towards the end of the three-year forecast.
The economy should also grow with strong interest in British goods thanks to the weak pound, offsetting a lower percentage of consumer spending.
The decision comes a year after rates were cut to 0.025% in August last year in response to the shock EU referendum vote, which sent the pound tumbling.
The bank estimates that full unification of prices and the economy will take at least four years.
Ahead of the bank&#39;s latest rate decision, many were calling for a rate hike with rising inflation putting increasing pressure on households. Three politicians called for an increase to 0.5% in June.
Inflation fell back to 2.6% last month from June&#39;s 2.9%, despite the bank saying it had expected such a change and that inflation should rise again over the course of next month.
The bank said the overshoot relative to the 2% target was &quot;entirely&quot; due to the weak pound.
Andrew Montlake, director of Coreco Mortgage Brokers, said: “Given the recent fall in swap rates, it looks like competition in the mortgage market will only increase as lenders start to compete for contracts with an eye to a good outlook towards the end of the year.
The market looks particularly good for those coming to the end of existing contracts and re-mortgages - there are no-fee options on offer, as well as the low rates that are gaining in popularity.”
NHS to prescribe controversial HIV drug to 10,000 patients
Patients will gain access to a &#39;transformative&#39; HIV prevention treatment from September following a High Court ruling on NHS drug funding.
England&#39;s National Health Service (NSH) has announced that the pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) pill, which is taken before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 per cent, will be offered through the health service to around 10,000 patients in a three-year trial times.
The NSH agreed to fund the trial after the Court of Appeal upheld a High Court ruling last year saying the NHS had the funding to pay for PrEP despite a statement that the drug should be funded by local authorities.
The decision, which was announced on Thursday, was hailed by NHS England chief executive Simon Stevens as a &#39;significant intervention&#39;, while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a &#39;watershed moment&#39;.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start accepting patients. Further clinics will join in October and full implementation will take place across England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV medication given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission among at-risk patients.
Applying PrEP before sex means that there is a sufficient amount of specific drugs in the patient&#39;s body to prevent infection.
These medications can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Tested patients include gay or bisexual men, transsexual people, and people with HIV-positive partners who are not receiving successful treatment.
Clinics will identify eligible participants who will sign consent to participate in testing, including men, women, transsexual people, and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with a GP in the UK can also apply at their local sexual health clinic to potentially take part in the trial.
The program will cost taxpayers £10 million and NHS England signed a contract this week to distribute the drugs after winning an international contract.
The trial is designed to gather clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation at scale.
Simon Stevens added: &#39;This important intervention should complement and fully leverage the ever-expanding and increasingly successful HIV prevention effort.
It is another milestone in the more than thirty-year effort to stop one of the biggest challenges to human health.&#39;
Deborah Gold, Chief Executive of the National Aids Trust (NAT), said: &#39;We are witnessing a defining moment in the fight against HIV.
If administered correctly and to patients at risk, PrEP offers the potential to transform England&#39;s HIV epidemic.
From September, NSH will offer patients at high risk of HIV infection a powerful new tool that is individually controlled and does not require persuasion from a partner, which will improve the quality of many lives.
We accept this statement with pleasure.&#39;
Ian Green, chief executive of the Terrence Higgins Trust said: &#39;The number one priority must be to rapidly deploy tests across the country; we must ensure its availability to every patient.
We now have the trial drug PrEP available and are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV infection.&#39;
Shadow Health Secretary Sharon Hodgson said: &#39;The start of the PrEP trial is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delays and delays by the Government.
The evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending the transmission of this life-threatening infection.
Subsequent tests will bring us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that we start testing as soon as possible across the country to protect those who are exposed to HIV and together stop the spread of HIV in society.&#39;
High-end living: a mezzanine and clever design have turned this small flat on Earls Court into a spacious home
Joanne Leigh, a former banker with a passion for property, swapped a large house in Knightsbridge for a flat on Earls Court in 2014.
It is located on the first floor of a smart Queen Anne terrace - and is an illustrative example of modern design that makes the most of the available space.
&quot;I used to live with my ex-husband in a much bigger house in Knightsbridge,&quot; Joanne said.
&quot;I was looking for something at a more reasonable price.
I came across this flat in Earls Court and it had the same ceiling height.
I immediately fell in love with him and nodded to him the same day.&quot;
Since then, the 1,000 square meter apartment has undergone a complete renovation.
A one bedroom apartment with a complicated layout - you had to go through the kitchen to get to the bedroom - Joanne wanted to add storage space and a mezzanine to take advantage of the high ceiling.
&quot;I wanted a high ceiling, big windows and lots of light.
Those were my demands,” she said.
To this end, she employed Erfan Azadi of Notting Hill-based designer and design studio Duck &amp; Shed and used the almost four-metre ceiling to create a home that was not just a project, but a place to live.
The ceiling did not reach such a height that two gaps could fit over each other - the challenge for the architects was to create a mezzanine on which you could walk upright.
Erfan had to engage his creative thinking.
&quot;Steel construction is quite complicated,&quot; he explained.
&quot;We had to arrange both spaces in such a way that we could walk upright.
It was not just about building a simple platform, but at the same time bending the steel structure so that it was at the right height above and below the ceiling.&quot;
This arrangement allowed Erfan to construct two full-fledged rooms on top of each other - while adding to the drama.
On the mezzanine, old copper window frames in Retrouvius design look down on the wonderful living room.
Gold mirrored furniture, silver lines and a retro Serge Mouille chandelier create a unique style.
The use of mirrors plays an important role in drama, space and lighting.
The short hallway is equipped with mirrors on both sides, making it look longer.
The mirror bar in the kitchen looks like a window to another room.
There are storage spaces equipped with mirrors for storing cutlery and glasses by the front door.
The advantage of the living room, which gives the whole apartment the impression of a significantly larger space, is the possibility of separating it from the kitchen when it is not in use.
Collapsible kitchens are nothing new.
However, what is unique about this solution are the folding doors.
&quot;We had to solve the technical side,&quot; says Erfan about the reinforced veneer doors.
&quot;The door is counterweighted so that it swings open very easily.&quot;
Thanks to the clever use of space and storage, Joanne gained an additional 16 square meters, a second room and a better overall layout of the apartment.
&quot;When it comes down to it, what you&#39;re selling is living space - or the value of your property,&quot; Erfan said.
&quot;Essentially, upon entering the apartment, the real estate agent calculates and estimates its price based on the living area.&quot;
In this case, it was possible to increase the living space while maintaining high-quality materials that give the space a luxurious look.
&quot;The material is very important because you touch it and create an emotional bond with the home,&quot; added Erfan.
&quot;You will not fall in love with the electrical distribution in the walls.
Yes, they are important, but they won&#39;t win your heart.”
As it turned out, quality design and an increase in living space can turn an ordinary apartment into an exceptional work.
And like Joanne, you may ultimately choose to stay.
The United States is coming apart.
The cultural and political divide between blue and red states is widening.
California has announced a travel ban for its citizens to Tennessee and seven other states.
The state of Tennessee retaliated by banning its citizens from traveling to California.
Of course, this is not a ban in the full sense of the word, US citizens can travel freely in all fifty states.
This is because California has banned spending state money on the trips of its citizens to eight other states, which are Alabama, South Dakota, Kansas, Kentucky, Mississippi, North Carolina, Tennessee and Texas.
Who will stop the madness?
California is strongly pro-LGBT and considers any expression of disapproval of the LGBT lifestyle to be discrimination.
However, Tennessee has passed a conscientious objection law, which states that a psychotherapist who has a moral problem with treating LGBT patients is not required to provide therapy to them, but is required to provide those patients with another therapist who does not have such a problem.
In turn, Texas and other states have passed laws under which religious charities that receive babies from mothers for adoption are not required to give those children up for adoption to same-sex couples.
Because of these conscientious objection laws, California has banned its citizens from funding travel to eight states.
In practice, this means that Californian professors may not have trips to scientific symposia in Texas, for example, reimbursed by their universities, because these are co-financed by the state of California.
Similarly, school sports teams cannot travel to tournaments or competitions, for example in Tennessee, with the financial support of their schools.
They have to get either federal grants for the trips, but it is absurd for the federal government to finance the trips of citizens from state A to state B, or private sponsorship.
The state of Tennessee has run out of patience and its legislature passed a law with a resolution that it also does not like California&#39;s policy of high taxes, high government spending, high deficits and tolerance of illegal immigrants, but still does not impose a travel embargo on California because of it.
He is imposing them in retaliation for California&#39;s travel embargo on Tennessee.
And the same will happen to any state of the union that would impose a similar travel ban on another state for any reason.
At the same time, he called on the parliaments of all states to stop this madness.
That&#39;s the facts, now the commentary.
The situation is toxic.
First, all of this is constitutional, nothing is unconstitutional.
States have the right to pass conscientious objection laws, as well as to decide what their money can and cannot be used for.
Second, what&#39;s wrong with conscientious objection?
If a butcher has a religious problem selling pork, why can&#39;t he just offer beef, lamb, poultry and fish?
Why force him to sell pork under the penalty of punishment, when there are enough butchers offering pork?
In Colorado, a baker is facing an anti-discrimination lawsuit and a hefty fine after he refused to bake a cake for a gay wedding.
But she also refuses to bake cakes for Halloween or cakes containing alcohol.
Why punish him and not leave him alone and order the appropriate cakes from hundreds of other bakers?
Thirdly, the beauty of the federal system is that the constitutional rights of all citizens of the federation are guaranteed, but individual states can adjust internal, domestic politics in non-federal powers according to their own preferences, i.e. according to the preferences of their residents.
Then there is variety, variety, diversity.
California can be California and Texas can be Texas.
But California wants California to be California and Texas and seven other states to be California too!
Fourth, members of the LGBT community once legitimately sought tolerance for their lifestyle.
Today, many members of this community follow the live-and-let-live rule that all reasonable people should follow, but some activists strive not for tolerance of themselves and others, but for extreme intolerance of others.
According to them, no one can ever again show moral, religious or philosophical disagreement with the LGBT lifestyle, and if they do, they should be criminalized.
The mentality of these activists is totalitarian.
They are the modern enemies of freedom.
Fifth, I don&#39;t know of a situation in American history where states made such deliberate decisions on political issues, except for one case.
Even in the days of the struggle for the civil rights of blacks, when the North and the West were on the side of integration and the South on the side of segregation, the states did not impose sanctions on each other.
The only case was the 1850s, the political cause was slavery, and a war between the North and the South was looming.
Of course, nothing like that will happen now, but the situation is still toxic.
The cultural and political divide between the blue Democratic states and the red Republican states is widening and the US is mentally disconnecting internally.
Unauthorized agitation.
Critic of Putin received a hefty fine.
Russian opposition politician Alexei Navalny was fined 300,000 rubles for violating campaign rules ahead of next year&#39;s presidential election.
The court fined him for inciting people to participate in unauthorized demonstrations.
Navalny has organized two large anti-government street protests in the past two months and announced that he wants to run for the post of head of state next March.
Incumbent Kremlin chief Vladimir Putin has yet to announce his candidacy, but is widely expected to do so and win again.
Navalny said the police came to his home in the morning and took him to court.
The latter fined him for calling people to demonstrations through videos posted on the Internet portal YouTube.
The fine is three hundred thousand.
&quot;We&#39;ll deduct them from the judge&#39;s salary later,&quot; joked a Kremlin critic on Twitter.
Russia&#39;s election commission recently concluded that Navalny cannot run in the presidential election because he was previously convicted of embezzlement.
However, Navalny, who is considered a fighter against corruption, considers the relevant sentence to be politically motivated.
On Thursday, the court also imposed fines of 300,000 rubles, or 25,000 rubles, on two members of Navalny&#39;s campaign team, Leonid Volkov and Nikolai Lyaskin.
Navalny entered Russian politics as an anti-corruption blogger and gradually became a dominant figure in the fragmented opposition scene.
The authorities are trying to prevent Navalny in the campaign in every possible way.
In February, he was sentenced to a five-year suspended sentence for robbing the Kirovles forestry enterprise.
In May, the appeals court upheld the verdict.
The verdict is thus final, which prevents Navalny from running for office under Russian law.
The brothers are fighting for an empire worth over 500 million dollars
Two brothers are now vying for one of Victoria&#39;s most expensive properties, worth more than $500 million, more than four decades after their Italian family founded an empire.
Former Carlton Football Club director and property developer Colin De Lutis lives on the Toorak estate, just three rooms from his younger brother Paul, who has taken a dispute over joint property and business assets to the High Court.
Paul wanted to leave the family business back in 2014, but the bitter dispute is constantly being contested in the Supreme Court.
Together with their mother Anna, the brothers own a total of 38 properties worth more than half a billion dollars. The first store was bought by the family in 1973 on Smith Street in Collingwood.
It was here that the family founded Westco Jeans, which grew into a chain of 160 brick-and-mortar stores.
In 1999, the family sold the entire company for $85 million.
The money has been used to buy other properties and the De Lutis portfolio now includes offices, development land in Brunswick and Sorrento, apartments on the Gold Coast and Mt Buller and suburban shopping centres.
Paul owns approximately one-third of the company&#39;s assets, while his father Colin, who Paul says is a &quot;significant driving force and dominant figure&quot; in the De Lutis family, owns just under two-thirds of the assets.
Court filings state that Colin owns $316 million in real estate, while Paul manages $176 million in real estate.
For Paul, it was precisely the distribution of property and financial resources that became problematic.
&quot;Colin&#39;s motion was overwhelmingly in his favor in my eyes,&quot; Paul wrote in a 2015 court affidavit.
Last Friday, after several failed attempts at reconciliation, the first session of the Supreme Court took place.
The brothers are also now vying for control of the existing business - from which Paul says Colin cut him off.
Colin counters that this is not true and accuses Paul of mishandling some of the properties.
In a previous affidavit, Colin said he believed in a successful resolution of the conflict.
&quot;My Italian background dictates to me that family is the most important thing,&quot; he wrote.
Court costs are rising. Hundreds of pages of affidavits, emails and reports from firms including Deloitte, Pitcher Partners and Charter Keck Cramer have swamped barristers, including Allan Myers, QC, and barristers for both sides.
Mrs. De Lutis and her late husband, Luigi, were Italian immigrants who had run milk bars and delis since the 1950s and bought a shop in Brunswick in the 1970s.
With the money raised from the property development, they bought a property in Collingwood, where Colin opened the family&#39;s first jeans business.
Colin said that when he started Westco &quot;in his senior year of college, Paul was still a little boy, about 10 years old.&quot;
Anna De Lutis said that together with Luigi, who died in 2012, they hoped that the transfer of the property to the sons would go smoothly.
&quot;Luigi often said he never wanted his sons to end up in court,&quot; she wrote.
The other two brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of the De Lutis family group of companies. Colin stated that Mark was compensated $10 million and Luke $26 million upon his departure.
As Paul stated, both Luke and Mark &quot;were not satisfied with the terms of their financial compensation&quot;.
Colin has held back ever since, despite being a former AFL club board member, according to Eddie McGuire, a well-known TV personality and Colin&#39;s best friend, in his 2015 autobiography.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul de Lutis and their lawyers on Friday.
Only Colin responded via text message, stating that due to the fact that the dispute is being resolved in court, &quot;I have nothing to add.&quot;
&quot;It is very sad that my brother Paul has decided to take this matter to court,&quot; he wrote.
In mid-2016, in one of the statements in court, Colin said that he tried to adapt to his brother&#39;s demands.
&quot;Our father would be very displeased if he saw our current situation,&quot; he said, adding that he &quot;still hopes for a successful solution.&quot;
On Friday, all hope was lost.
&quot;Our disputes will be settled in court soon,&quot; Colin wrote.
It&#39;s hot in the Czech Republic.
The teachers shower the children.
Public transport drivers pack water and summer clothes.
At Na Chodovci kindergarten in Prague 4, which currently has about 35 children, they only go out in the morning.
The nursery has been renovated and the planted trees do not yet provide much shade.
There is no swimming pool, but the teachers shower the children in the nebula.
In the afternoon, the children stay in the classrooms, where the blinds and curtains are closed.
They try to cool the air with an air purifier because they don&#39;t have air conditioning.
It is also challenging for female teachers and cooks.
&quot;The temperature inside and outside exceeds the hygiene limits for kindergartens, so we shouldn&#39;t even be open during this period,&quot; said the director of the kindergarten, Miloslava Makovičková.
There is a glass corridor in the kindergarten where, according to her, the temperature is around 40 degrees.
We ventilate in the morning after 6 o&#39;clock, the windows are closed and we have blinds on the south sides to protect ourselves.
&quot;But it won&#39;t help much,&quot; she added.
They have better conditions in the Na Hrázi forest nursery in Hostivice, where the children spend most of their time outside.
We have mature trees on the property, so we are under them.
