Kelly&#39;s diagnosis actually makes sense, but many of his predecessors have gnashed their teeth at the scrutiny of Trump and his presentation in the media.
Trump&#39;s relationship with the media goes back decades — and now that he&#39;s in the White House, his habit of watching TV news is even stronger.
&quot;If Trump as a candidate was upset by honest reporting, it was convenient to show him that there was a lot of other media that was talking about him in a positive light that was easier to convince,&quot; Sam Nunberg, a former campaign adviser, told Politico in February.
Politico&#39;s Tara Palmeri wrote at the time that &quot;the key to keeping Trump&#39;s tweets in check -- at least according to six former organizers of his campaign -- is making sure Trump regularly follows the media that sings his praises.&quot;
Good.
However, the idea that Trump&#39;s tendency to post his opinions on Twitter was ever &quot;under control&quot; is ludicrous.
Maybe these campaign organizers know something others don&#39;t -- that Trump&#39;s tweets would be more outrageous if they weren&#39;t vetted.
We will most likely never know about the tweets that Trump never sent.
If his employees managed to keep him at bay at least a few times, then their efforts were not in vain.
However, no one has yet been able to regularly prevent Trump from inciting controversial topics.
Part of the problem is that in a White House made up of rival factions, people regularly try to advance their agenda by feeding the Trumps materials — which may or may not be reliable — that support their worldview.
The Politico portal, which covered the issue from all sides, published a report in May about the propensity of advisers to present questionable information to the head of state.
This is an example of such information from the pen of reporter Shane Goldmacher:
“Current and former Trump officials say the president often reacts very angrily to negative media reports, particularly leaks, and seeks to trace their origins.
This situation arose in late February when someone slipped the president a copy of an article from GotNews.com - the website of provocateur Charles C. Johnson - that accused Deputy Chief of Staff Katie Walsh of being the &#39;source of many leaks&#39; from the White House.
