Lavender from Provence is threatened by climate change
Lavender has become a symbol of Provence in the south-eastern region of France, but is now threatened by climate change.
Lavender is dwindling due to a dry climate and harmful insects, causing consternation on the faces of researchers and farmers looking for a solution.
Eric Chaisse, an expert at the agricultural research institute CRIEPPAM in Provence said: &quot;Lavender cultivation in Provence is at risk because in the last few years this plant has been exposed to climate changes that bring with it less rainfall in spring and autumn.
This affects the longevity of the lavender.
Cicadas and grasshoppers carrying micro-bacteria that thrive in dry climates are also to blame.&#39;
The stakes are high.
Lavender attracts tourists and the oil produced from it is an important ingredient in perfumes and cosmetics.
Eric Chaisse said: “Instead of long and beautiful flowers, smaller, underdeveloped and often weak plants grow.
The amount of oil obtained from these lavenders is understandably less.”
A possible solution may be to distribute water more efficiently and slow down the evaporation of water from the soil, but also to spray lavender with a protective mixture of clay and water and breed more species resistant to dry weather.
The murder of the journalist highlights the growing threats in Mexico
The staff of the Riodoce Weekly meets regularly every Wednesday to discuss news regarding the ongoing unrest in the Sinaloa region involving organized crime, corrupt officials and the relentless drug wars.
Today, however, under the onslaught of recent events, they gather mainly for their own safety.
They learn that it is important for them to change their habits.
Two distinguished journalists talk about what would be safer: taking their children with them to an office that was attacked with a grenade in 2009, or leaving them at home.
Security experts wrote three simple words on the blackboard: adversaries, neutrals, and allies.
They ask journalists to put names to each word - no evidence needed, just use your imagination and hunch.
What to choose - drug dealers, politicians, businessmen and journalists are suspected of taking money from the government or drug cartels - a catalog of criminals whose job it is to cover up criminal activity.
The violence continues and bodies pile up across the country; journalists among them are steadily increasing: according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, there are at least 25 since President Enrique Pena Nieto came to power in December 2012; 589 journalists are under federal protection after attacks and threats; and in all seven states, seven have been killed this year.
Among them also co-founder of the periodical Riodioce, editor and inspiration for colleagues, Javier Valdez Cardenas.
&quot;The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and working as a journalist,&quot; Valdez wrote in one of his many books on the violence linked to the drug trade.
His loss is palpable, even as his presence is all-pervasive - a large photo of Valdez with the words &quot;Justice&quot; on it, pointing his middle finger, hangs in the facade of the building; two journalists - Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez - over the age of 30, wearing a T-shirt with a photo of Valdez with a smile on his face, glasses on his nose and a Panama hat.
The meeting takes place less than two months after his death; journalists talk about mutual traumas, nightmares, insomnia and paranoia.
Although a special federal prosecutor&#39;s office was established in 2010 to handle journalist cases, it has so far prosecuted two suspects, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
Most of the thousands of murders that occur each year are linked to drug trafficking and organized crime. Murderers of journalists thus very rarely end up in court.
Journalists from Riodoc insist on reporting on the violence happening in Sinaloa; even though they are devastated by grief and said territory is currently very treacherous.
Without information about the killers and no vision of justice, the security meeting is pointless, Ibarra says.
&quot;It&#39;s foolish to waste time on such meetings,&quot; he adds.
&quot;Unless we get more information, no one can be trusted.&quot;
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left Riodoc&#39;s headquarters in Culiacán, the capital of Sinaloa.
He managed to drive a few blocks when his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men who pulled him out of the car and shot him dead with 12 bullets, apparently because of the title of the article - which can be translated as Twelfth River.
The shooters then got into his car and crashed it not far from the crime scene.
Valdez died at the age of 50.
He left behind a wife and two grown children.
Rumors seem to travel fast in Culiacan.
In Valdez&#39;s case, however, there is a suspicious silence.
Since Guzmán&#39;s arrest last year and his extradition to the United States in January, Sinaloa has become one of the country&#39;s bloodiest battlegrounds as rival factions seek to fill the void.
Every day, several people are killed on the streets of Sinaloa, and the cemetery is full of ornate two-story mausoleums for drug kingpins, many of them larger than houses.
Forget for a moment that the word &quot;ceasefire&quot; means that one drug cartel controls a coastal state with valuable ports and important drug routes into the United States.
Despite this, as well as the fact that Valdez was intimately familiar with the risks of his job, Ismail Bojorquez, 60, Riodoc&#39;s co-founder and director, still blames himself for failing to protect his friend.
They believe two acts of misconduct contributed to his death.
The first was the February edition of an interview with Damaso Lopez, the leader of one of the rival drug cartels that waged war with the sons of Joaquín Guzmán.
Peace might have angered the sons; suspected gang members bought up all copies of the paper the moment it hit the shelves.
The second mistake was not forcing Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after seizing another newspaper that carried the same story.
Valdez has become a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his death is seen as an important milestone in the fight against journalists by Mexican criminals.
He managed to survive for so long and all his friends and colleagues believed that this would never change.
He was practically a veteran of the Noroeste periodical when he decided to sell his $50 shares in 2003 and found Riodoc together with five colleagues.
In Sinaloa, &quot;it was impossible to do journalism without mentioning the drug trade,&quot; Bojorquez said.
Over time, Riodoce gained a reputation for brave and truthful reporting; the newspaper began to prosper.
Journalists were happy to search for problematic topics and publish texts without censorship - readers were fascinated to read stories that no one else dared to publish.
Eight years after its founding, Riodoce won the prestigious Maria Moors Cabot Award for reporting on Latin America.
That same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award from the Committee to Protect Journalists for his brave reporting on the Mexican drug trade.
Valdez openly admitted that he was scared.
&quot;I was afraid for my life,&quot; he said when accepting the award.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa is &quot;a way of life,&quot; Valdez said in an interview with Rompeviento TV last October.
“You have to take on the role of a journalist - or play the fool.
I don&#39;t want to be asked, &#39;What were you doing in the face of death... why didn&#39;t you say what was going on?&#39;&quot;
Riodoc employees miss Valdez. The man was known for his joking and indiscriminate language. He was a good friend who loved to give advice and hugs - a teacher who knew how to survive.
Everyone relied on his daily routine.
He always wore his cap.
He often went to the El Guayabo bar opposite the offices and sat at the same table.
Now they ask: did this routine cause his death?
His death also made them question their own assumptions - how do they do their best work and stay alive?
&quot;They don&#39;t like you messing with their wives, children, clean shops, secret airstrips.&quot;
&quot;These things were forbidden,&quot; Bojorquez stated.
As a result, there is a high level of self-censorship and self-preservation.
You have to trust your instincts.
If you feel that something is wrong here, hands off.
The trouble is, said Riodoc editor Andres Villarreal, that &quot;smell is a sense that can be fooled ... and then the Javier thing happened.&quot;
The old rules, he and others say, no longer apply in Sinaloa -- as they do in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states that are home to a toxic mix of lucrative smuggling routes, weak governments and corrupt politicians.
The landscape is constantly changing.
No cell phones are allowed in the room where Riodoc staff meet; a few days ago, spyware was discovered that governments were buying to monitor Mexican journalists and activists.
Outside the building, two policemen find relief from the forty-degree heat in the shade of a nearby tree.
They were chosen by the state to protect the Riodoc offices, which are located in a four-story building in the bourgeois district of Culiacan.
Journalists are wondering if these police officers are not among the 50 percent of law enforcement officers who, according to the government, are corrupt.
It has been several months since journalists last ventured into the mountainous regions that are essentially controlled by drug cartels.
There are three main stories on the agenda this week.
The first of these is the murder of the brother of former boxer Julio César Chávez in Sinaloa.
They also shed light on suspicious government spending that took place in the hometown of the state governor.
There have also recently been several kidnappings at one of Culiacán&#39;s most luxurious restaurants, just a block from the prosecutor&#39;s office.
No one has officially released the identity of the abductees or the circumstances of the abduction, so journalists were wary of writing about what every resident of the city knows: that the restaurant is a favorite destination for drug dealers and politicians.
One of the journalists read from public records that the restaurant in question was registered under a name associated with a certain politician who is a member of the Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), which has dominated all levels of the political scene for almost the entire last century.
Several PRI governors have recently been accused of high-level corruption.
Villarreal asked journalists to write about earlier incidents that had occurred at the restaurant, including one in which one of Joaquín &quot;El Chapo&quot; Guzmán&#39;s sons escaped an army task force.
Just a month ago, readers would have read about this topic in Valdez&#39;s column, which was the best source of information about kidnappings.
&quot;Valdez would definitely crack the case,&quot; said Villarreal, 46, who is nicknamed &quot;El Flaco&quot; for his slim frame.
