Dinosaurs used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, however terrifying.
Researchers have now revealed the conclusions of the first findings of an amazing creature the size of a rhinoceros, whose perfectly preserved remains - which experts have dubbed the &#39;Mona Lisa of dinosaurs&#39; - were found by a Canadian miner.
The remains were so well preserved that experts were able to determine the reddish-brown color of its scaly skin and said the dinosaur had a &#39;troubled past&#39;.
An article in the journal Current Biology stated that it is &#39;the best-preserved armored dinosaur ever found and one of the finest dinosaur species in the world&#39;.
The fossil is a new species of the family Nodosauridae. The dinosaur lived during the Cretaceous Period, about 110 to 112 million years ago.
Its perfectly preserved state literally shocked the researchers, who described it with the words &#39;remarkable indeed&#39;.
According to National Geographic, the armored herbivore is the best-preserved fossil of its species to date.
Behind the discovery is Shawn Funk, who discovered the fossil on March 21, 2011 while drilling in the Suncor Millennium mine near Alberta, Canada.
He came across what appeared to be a foreign object and decided to examine it more closely.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
Researchers spent the next six years working to unearth the animal from a huge 1,100 kg chunk of earth.
Once the work is complete, the dinosaur is ready to be unveiled.
&#39;You just squint a little and you&#39;ll believe it&#39;s asleep,&#39; said Caleb Brown, project manager and naturalist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the animal is on display.
&#39;It will certainly go down in history as one of the most beautiful and well-preserved species of dinosaur - the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs.&#39;
By studying its skin, the researchers found that this herbivore - despite being covered in armor and resembling a walking tank - very likely faced a serious threat from carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to protect against predators and used a camouflage system used by many animals today.
Experts say this allowed him to better blend in with his surroundings and avoid enemies. The camouflage system suggests that it was a favorite food of larger dinosaurs.
News of the 110-million-year-old dinosaur of the Nodosauridae family first appeared in newspapers in May. It is currently available for viewing at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
The researchers named it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, who spent more than 7,000 hours painstakingly uncovering the fossil with his team.
Thanks to the amazingly well-preserved state of the fossil, Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists document the patterns and shape of scales and armor throughout the body.
They discovered a camouflage method commonly used by today&#39;s animals for defense - the upper part of the animal was darker than its lower part.
Although this masking effect is common in nature, the researchers&#39; findings are surprising because Borealopelta&#39;s size far exceeds today&#39;s animals using the same technique.
So it is possible that the dinosaur was such an abundance of predators that evolution prioritized camouflage over confrontation for survival.
Many contemporary animals with camouflage - for example deer, zebra and or armadillo - are much smaller and also more vulnerable as prey, which suggests that Nosodaurus had to literally fight for its survivors.
&#39;The predation of a huge and heavily armored dinosaur vividly illustrates the danger posed by predators in the Cretaceous period,&#39; said Brown.
Chemical analysis of the organic components contained in the scales also revealed that the dinosaur&#39;s skin was probably reddish-brown in color.
Researchers are continuing to study the animal and look for more clues about its life, including preserved stomach contents, to track down its last meal.
They believe that the dinosaur fell into the river after death and was carried to the sea, where it sank to the bottom.
The Alberta region at that time had the same climate as present-day Florida, and the rivers and oceans extended much further inland than they do today.
&#39;This nodosaurus is really remarkable in that it is completely covered in perfectly preserved scaly skin, and at the same time it is preserved in three dimensions, so we can see its original size,&#39; said Brown.
&#39;For these reasons the animal looks practically the same as it did in the Cretaceous period.
You don&#39;t have to use your imagination to reconstruct it; just close your eyes a little and it seems as if he is only sleeping.&#39;
During the Cretaceous period, giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs that moved on two legs, roamed the earth.
Although the king of all dinosaurs - Tyrannosaurus rex - lived several million years after Borealopelta, this armored dinosaur may have been the favorite prey of its equally fearsome ancestors.
These include the Acrocanthosaurus, a 11.5 meter long monster weighing over 6 tonnes.
The researchers, whose latest findings were published in the journal Current Biology, believe that Borealopeltus&#39; body was washed out to sea after being mummified in the mud.
Shawn Funk, who discovered the fossil on March 21, 2011 while drilling at the Suncor Millennium mine near Alberta, Canada, is behind the discovery.
According to the museum, it is the best-preserved armored dinosaur in the world, including skin and armor, and is also complete from snout to hip.
The animal reached an average length of 5 meters and weighed up to 1300 kg.
Two 50 cm spikes protruded from his shoulders.
Researchers believe this herbivore roamed what is now Canada until it ended up in a river that washed it out to sea.
His underwater tomb preserved the body in perfect condition.
The fossil remains of this species are preserved to the extent that the armored plates around the skull still cover the remnants of the skin.
As Michael Greshko wrote for National Geographic, &#39;finding such a preserved individual can be compared to winning the lottery.
The longer I watch him, the more shocking the find seems to me.
The fossil remains of this species are preserved to the extent that the armored plates around the skull still cover the remnants of the skin.
At his side lies his right front foot with toes pointing up.
I can easily count the scales on his foot.&#39;
How one activist learned the answer to the question: &#39;Whose Streets?&#39;
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shaking all over.
The day after she arrived in New York, the native of St. Louis sat on the bed in the Airbnb room and scrolled through Facebook posts on her phone.
In the process, she came across a post from a high school student.
&quot;The police have just shot and killed an 18-year-old youth whose body is still lying in the street,&quot; it read.
She was surprised that no one else had written this post to her, so she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
User @TheePharoah kept retweeting her wall posts.
Rapper from St. Louis was tweeting about the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old who was shot and killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a photo of Brown&#39;s body lying lifeless on the street, where no one had taken him four hours later.
This is crazy, Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new to her and her community.
She put her phone down to go back to it that evening when she was following tweets about people gathering on Canfield Drive.
She watched photos of police tapes and people screaming. One of the men claimed to be the father of the victim and was holding a sign that read &quot;Ferguson Police Killed My Unarmed Son&quot;!
She was watching the live news - one of the police officers was standing in front of a group of protesters, holding a leash in his hand and a barking dog on the other end.
In another video, another police officer, she said, held a gun and pointed it at the crowd, shouting: &quot;I&#39;m going to kill you all... animals.&quot;
This is not normal, Ferrell told herself.
“This is not the type of murder we are used to and can call normal.
I felt goosebumps all over my body.
&quot;I was angry and I cried.&quot;
She immediately booked a return flight and traveled home the next day.
After landing at 11:00 p.m., she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father and decided they would head to Ferguson in the morning.
The story of what happened to Ferrell and the city of Ferguson over the next three years is told in the new documentary &quot;Whose Streets?&quot;, which opens in theaters on August 11.
It&#39;s a story of survival and protest, love and resistance, strength and resilience, told from the perspective of people living in a community who take to the streets to demand answers.
On the way to Ferguson, Ferrell struck up a dialogue with her daughter -- dressed in a floral jersey and matching floral headband -- about a topic they had discussed many times before -- &quot;the black experience.&quot;
&quot;Remember how I taught you about how black people had to fight for what they believed in?&quot; she recalls of the conversation.
&quot;We&#39;re going to Ferguson right now because the police killed an 18-year-old and that&#39;s not right.&quot;
&quot;It was out of the question not to take her with me,&quot; Ferrell later said.
&quot;Today&#39;s events are the culmination... of what happened in the past.
She had to know it and see it with her own eyes and grow up in it.
She needed to develop not only in activism and organizing, but at the same time she needed to know the difference between the different layers of the black experience and what we need to do to liberate ourselves.
Despite the fact that I am able to provide her with conditions in which she does not experience racism firsthand, she is in no way different from any other black child-woman.
I feel that if I shielded her from this experience, I would only be doing her a disservice.”
After arriving in Ferguson, the first stop was South Florissant Road across from the police department, which became a base for activists awaiting word from Officer Darren Wilson about his possible involvement in the incident.
Here, Ferrell and her daughter met a local businessman who prepared food for others.
Together they prepared food in bags and helped deliver it to the Protestants.
In Ferrell&#39;s eyes, a new type of activism was slowly born.
&quot;My activism turned upside down after August 9,&quot; Ferrell said, adding that while studying at the University of Missouri-St. Louis was president of the Minority Student Nurses Assn. and sought to introduce health care and food in black communities.
&quot;I had no experience with the organization.
It was natural.”
A few weeks later, Ferrell met the documentary&#39;s later co-director, Sabaah Folayan, during an evening demonstration.
Folayan said that he and her cameraman, Lucas Alvarado-Farrar, &quot;just wanted to document&quot; the ongoing events.
But Ferrell wondered, &quot;Are you working on a documentary or trying to find a story to use?&quot;
That type of skepticism permeated the community through many people, often white, who wanted to capitalize on pain and determination.
As Folayan explained in an unreleased interview, &quot;We heard that the voices of people who are born and raised in Ferguson are very often neglected, and we wanted to change that.&quot;
Folayan has already teamed up with co-director Damon Davis, who is a well-respected local death row artist.
His involvement in the project also intrigued Ferrell, along with six other local residents who were followed by the &quot;Whose Streets?&quot; team in the years following Brown&#39;s murder.
&quot;No one speaks for us in this document, but it is our testimony,&quot; Davis said.
&quot;That was important to me - how these people would be represented - because in the same way I would be represented.&quot;
While the documentary didn&#39;t aim to focus on Ferrell&#39;s experiences — in an effort to portray that the movement is &quot;not about a savior leader, it&#39;s about bringing the community together,&quot; Folayan said — she appeared to be the most open to participating in the filming.
The documentary &quot;Whose Streets?&quot; thus describes a very personal aspect of Ferrell&#39;s life, for example how he fell in love with his wife.
&quot;I felt like I was naked,&quot; Ferrell said with a smile on her face as she thought about the first moment she saw the final version of the documentary.
&quot;But I realized that in order to do this work and humanize black people, I had to open up.&quot;
In addition, Ferrell&#39;s story highlights the queer black woman&#39;s role in the larger aspect of the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the movement&#39;s three founders — who created the #BlackLivesMatter social media campaign in response to the 2012 killing of teenager Trayvon Martin — call themselves queers.
“Black queer women in leadership positions are ultimately what keep the movement alive,” Ferrell said, “because we&#39;re constantly fighting on multiple fronts.
Black queer women have to bear the brunt of these events.”
Folayan agrees, adding that &quot;the movement is actually supported by black women and a lot of queer black women.&quot;
However, she insists that &quot;this is not just an affirmative action thing&quot; and that Ferrell is not the main character of the documentary because of her views.
&quot;She was the driving force and source of energy,&quot; she said.
&quot;It&#39;s no coincidence that she&#39;s on the front lines, because life at these intersections as a queer black woman is dangerous.
You can feel that rush of energy even in front of the screen.&quot;
Meanwhile, back in Ferguson, the television cameras have cleared their positions, but the strained racial ties between the community and the police remain.
Ferrell is serving a two-and-a-half-year sentence for blocking a freeway during demonstrations.
She described the socio-political climate in the area she calls home as &quot;a mess.&quot;
Nevertheless, she does not stop in her pursuit, which she has committed to since she hit the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
&quot;It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We must love and support each other.
All we have to lose are our chains.”
