A Becoming Resemblance: artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning&#39;s DNA
In the center of one of the rooms of New York&#39;s Fridman Gallery, there are several faces of different skin tones - white, black and brown - suspended from the ceiling on wires. Each of them seemed to fall out of the eye of the previous one.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from oral swabs and hair sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth prison, where the former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for unauthorized publication of classified cables on WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her experience in technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transsexual and trailblazing dissident whose sentence was commuted by Obama three days before he left office as US president.
By algorithmically analyzing Manning&#39;s DNA and using 30 portraits to represent what a person with that genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg creates a sharp, if not intellectual, commentary on the malleability of DNA - as well as the many ways in which DNA can be interpreted - and the inherent determinism of these interpretations as well as identities.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward Manning, has talked about identifying as a woman since she was young. She was convicted in 2013 on twenty counts, including violating six espionage laws, computer fraud and theft.
All her photos were withheld by prison staff. Only one low-quality black-and-white photo has been leaked to the public, showing a visibly distressed Manning sitting in the driver&#39;s seat wearing the platinum blonde wig with which she is now associated.
In 2015, positive reactions to Dewey-Hagborg&#39;s 2012 project Stranger Visions were still reverberating.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic objects - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create an image of the possible forms of these people.
And it was at this time that she received an email from Paper Magazine.
&quot;They were going to interview Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted to supplement the article with a portrait,&quot; Dewey-Hagborg explained at the opening of the new exhibition.
However, visits and photography were not allowed, so they approached Chelsea to ask if she would be interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became friends over the course of two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoila Kanunga, which presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea was pardoned and allowed to attend the exhibition in person.
President Obama actually asked for Manning&#39;s release days after the comic was published, a welcome change after several excruciating years in a military prison in Kansas.
It&#39;s interesting, indeed, that the exhibition is taking place at a time when Donald Trump is waging war on government whistleblowers and transgender soldiers, all while trying to find new ways to tweet resentment in areas he&#39;s supposed to support.
Asked about the odd timing, Dewey-Hagborg said that &quot;everything happens for a reason.&quot;
Beneath an artist statement on one of the gallery walls, Manning calls with her huge signature (the &quot;i&quot; in her last name dotted with a heart) for an end to &quot;self-perpetuating factionalism based on gender, race, sexuality and culture.&quot;
On the opposite side are the sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - the centipede letters C, G and A recorded in pencil.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the artist&#39;s sophisticated scientific dictionary), Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar we all are, at least biologically.
&quot;What I hope people take away from this is that our genome doesn&#39;t care who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret it in their own way,&quot; Dewey-Hagborg said. Her video-themed work Spurious Memories from 2007 is also on display.
&quot;DNA tells many different stories, this is 30 of them.&quot;
The last specimen of the exhibition, located in a separate room, is a single page from the aforementioned graphic novel.
It shows Manning emerging King Kong-style from the United States Disciplinary Barracks, megaphone in hand.
&quot;Once they prevent you from speaking, they win,&quot; it reads.
&quot;Never be silenced.&quot;
&quot;It&#39;s a direct transcription from one of the letters,&quot; said the Philadelphia artist.
&quot;It gives me goosebumps just thinking about it.&quot;
Manning has yet to visit the exhibition in person - as foretold in the comics - but when she does, she will be greeted in the center of the room by her masks, her own genomic likenesses, lined up like a crowd of Protestants.
Which was also the purpose of the exhibition, including a nearly 160 cm statue of Maning, on which her genetic haplogroups are recorded in pencil.
&quot;They&#39;ve been placed on walls in the past, but this time I wanted them to give off a sense of a crowd,&quot; Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
&quot;I wanted to give the impression of a mass movement taking on the form of Chelsea and liberating her.&quot;
