Red meat, dairy and chocolate may ease symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
Red meat and dairy can be a nightmare for your digestive system.
But a new study suggests just the opposite: a diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable disease, which affects up to 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 patients in the UK, causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhoea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually reminded to avoid meat and dairy products to relieve symptoms. However, researchers at the University of Washington found that the essential amino acid tryptophan found in the protein helps create immune cells that support gut resistance.
Study leader Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells protect the intestines and ensure that harmful microbes from food are broken down.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without harming sensitive tissue.
Once the scales are tipped to the side of inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can occur.
As part of the research, the scientists found the presence of immune cells supporting the body&#39;s tolerance in the stomach of mice with a specific bacterium.
This bacterium requires the presence of tryptophan - one of the building blocks of proteins - to form cells.
Professor Colonna said: &quot;We found a link between one type of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a common part of the gut microbiome and the development of cells that support the body&#39;s tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more of these immune cells they had.&quot;
He also suggested that if the same thing turns out to be true in humans, then the combination of L. reuteri bacteria and a tryptophan-rich diet would help develop a more tolerant and less inflammatory gut environment.
Postgraduate researcher dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, studying a type of immune cell that supports the body&#39;s tolerance, discovered that one group of test mice had these cells, while another group of the same mice, kept separately, lacked the cells.
She deduced that one group of mice had a different gut microbiome - the community of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally reside in the gastrointestinal tract.
The guts of the mice were tested by DNA sequencing, and the researchers found six types of bacteria in the mice with immune cells that the other group of mice lacked.
Mice that were raised in a sterile environment and lacked the gut microbiome - so they did not develop this type of immune cells - were given L. reuteri bacteria - and they developed immune cells.
To understand how the bacterium affects the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in liquid and then transferred small amounts of the liquid - without the bacterium - to undeveloped immune cells that were kept in isolation.
Immune cells evolved into tolerance cells.
After removing the active ingredient from the liquid, it was found to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indolyl-3-acetic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice&#39;s diet, the number of these cells increased by 50 percent. At the same time, after halving the doses of tryptophan, the number of cells fell by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerance cells as mice, and most of us harbor L. reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan byproducts from L. reuteri cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in humans with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan added: &quot;Each of us should probably strive to develop these cells because they control the inflammation of the inner surface of the intestines.
A potentially high level of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri can increase the cell population.”
