White House props cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
The White House&#39;s decision to fly a Navy helicopter onto the South Lawn for a celebration of America&#39;s manufacturing industry last month came to $24,000, according to Navy records released by TIME.
A green and white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter, also called Marine One with the president on board, was the highlight of the July 17 White House program, which was a showcase of America&#39;s design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and several senior White House officials viewed the display of products from all 50 states.
A helicopter from Connecticut was displayed alongside a yacht from Maine, a fire engine from Wisconsin and a forklift from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, requesting the helicopter&#39;s presence less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn as part of an &quot;extraordinary&quot; event, records from Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) -- the unit responsible for managing the helicopter -- said.
&quot;I wanted to make sure you were aware of such a significant event,&quot; the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, the Deputy Chief of Naval Aviation the day before the event began.
The report indicated that the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn at approximately 7:00 a.m. on July 17 for the parade, scheduled to begin at 3:00 p.m., and would remain in place until the entire site was cleared, which was scheduled to take place between 6:00 p.m. and 9:00 p.m.: 00.
The email went on to say that if there is a delay in the departure from the White House, a replacement crew will be sent for the return flight due to work hours regulations.
The original crew remained on site that evening, along with the helicopter, and with them a unit of security personnel.
From the records - obtained by the TIME weekly - it was not clear whether a second crew was eventually dispatched.
The Hatch Act prevents government officials from using government property for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating a possible violation of this regulation.
“We were wondering if this was a violation of the Hatch Act and were assured that everything was fine,” the commander wrote.
&quot;Sounds like you&#39;ve been blocked,&quot; the deputy commander wrote back.
This &quot;Made in America&quot; show was designated by the White House as an official event and thus would not be covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political undertones.
While attending the event, the president pushed for health care reform that was passing the Senate and talked about trying to rein in government regulation.
The use of air transport vehicles such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when traveling.
However, their presence purely for presentation reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered the review in February after the presidential jet taxied in the background at his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida. His Twitter account is flooded with complaints about his predecessor&#39;s use of the presidential plane.
&quot;The White House is pleased with the &#39;Made in America&#39; show, which showcased products from all 50 states that are made by Americans with American materials,&quot; said Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
The crews of the HMX-1 helicopter frequently practice landings in the Washington area and on the South Lawn, rehearsing possible arrivals with the President of the United States at the White House with the utmost precision.
While Trump attended the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 made 58 practice landings near the White House.
The flight to the Made in America show was part of current crew training, a government official said.
The helicopter unit flew another eleven hours on the same day as part of &quot;non-presidential support missions&quot;.
The White House said no other props were paid for with taxpayer money.
A Sikorsky spokesman said the company was in no way involved in negotiations to display the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep budget records for presidential flights, and exact costs related to the parade are difficult to determine, according to the Navy.
According to the Department of Defense, the hourly cost for fiscal year 2017, DoD cost reimbursements for the VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit&#39;s records indicate a time of 30 minutes from Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico, Virginia, and back.
The White House argues that the helicopter&#39;s actual operating costs are well below that figure.
&quot;To state the cost to taxpayers based on estimates for expense reimbursements is very misleading,&quot; Walters said of the matter.
&quot;These estimates include personnel, maintenance and many other hidden costs that are included in the annual cost.&quot;
According to a 2015 RAND study, DoD reimbursements do not include personnel costs, but do include the cost of fuel, maintenance, and contract costs.
Then-White House Press Secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of the helicopter for the parade.
&quot;The idea behind this week&#39;s show is to showcase products made in the U.S.,&quot; Spicer said.
“I am aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut take great pride in contributing to the defense of our state and employing hundreds, if not thousands, of people.
I think, like most Americans, that we are proud of the helicopter and other military equipment that countless American citizens have a hand in producing.
This fact deserves to be remembered.”
It&#39;s unclear if Trump also went to see the helicopter during his tour of the South Lawn. The only thing that can be said with certainty is that he got behind the wheel of one of the fire engines.
Back at the White House, Trump addressed Sikorsky representatives and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
&quot;I know Sikorsky very well,&quot; said the president, &quot;I own three myself.&quot;
