Police dogs practiced helicopter flyovers in Most
Dogs specialized in the search for explosives and search dogs practiced helicopter flyovers at Lake Most today.
A police dog must not be timid and afraid of flying, said Petr Tomášek, head of the police cynologists of the Ústí Region.
Training a police dog takes about two years.
At Most, both adult trained dogs and those still undergoing training practiced.
In addition to the standard training, during which they had to detect sharp samples of explosives around the lake and look for a lost extra, all 12 animals had to board a helicopter and fly over the lake.
The main purpose of the exercise is to test the dogs in the helicopter.
So that as soon as the helicopter lands, the dog can go to work, so that he does not have a problem with the helicopter ride.
&quot;The helicopter lands, the dog goes and immediately searches,&quot; said Tomášek.
A dog that is restless or is unable to start working immediately after the helicopter ride is excluded from training.
&quot;The dog handlers usually keep them in the garden, for example,&quot; Tomášek added.
The police have 76 dogs with various specializations in the Ústí Region.
German shepherds predominate, but Belgian shepherds are also increasing.
The handler has been taking care of him since he was a puppy.
&quot;He is raising him himself, preparing him for the service that the dog will do for us,&quot; Tomášek added.
The animal undergoes repeated veterinary examinations, which can reveal any health handicaps.
If the dog is healthy and fearless, it passes the first tests at 20 months.
&quot;It takes around two and a half to three years to get into a sharp intervention,&quot; Tomášek added.
The length of service with the police depends on the dog&#39;s health.
They mostly serve up to eight to ten years.
They usually live with their handlers.
