Get to know the plant in one click.
The new free application Pl@ntNet will help students with the creation of herbariums as well as ordinary plant lovers.
When they are wondering what plant they just came across on a walk, this application will advise them.
All they have to do is take a photo of the plant and the app will automatically recognize what kind it is.
The new application, which is available for both iOS and Android, was presented on Tuesday by representatives of the CEEV Center for Ethical and Environmental Education in Bratislava&#39;s Mountain Park as part of the Secret Life of the City project.
Pupils from 50 Czech and Slovak schools also participated in the project, and together with their teachers, they took photos and added plants from their surroundings to the database of the application.
The newly created French application is free to download on the Secret Life of the City website.
The main goal of the French programmers was for as many people as possible to contribute their images to the application, thereby increasing the number of plants that the application can recognize.
&quot;Already children who hold a tablet or mobile phone in their hand can go into the forest,&quot; said the coordinator of this project, Ivana Poláčková.
Based on a sufficiently high-quality photo of a flower, leaf or fruit of a plant, the application can recognize its name in a few seconds, which it then assigns under the photo in Czech and Slovak.
The French allowed us to translate the application into Slovak and Czech for the Secret Life of the City project.
It is therefore welcome for users to contribute an image of a plant that is not yet in the database after creating an account in the application.
&quot;The French will evaluate whether it is beneficial and then add it to the database,&quot; informed Poláčková.
GMB concerns about investment in McVitie&#39;s factory in Glasgow
Unions are seeking assurances from managers at biscuit maker McVitie&#39;s about a long-term commitment to production at the Glasgow factory.
The Scottish trade union GMB said the company was silent on the potential investment in the Tollcross factory for now.
More than 500 employees work in the factory, producing Hobnob biscuits and Rich Tea, among other products.
The owner of McVitie&#39;s, Pladis, said it had invested more than £5m in the area over the previous few years.
She added that employees and union representatives would be &quot;among the first to be notified&quot; of any changes to factory operations.
In a letter to the company&#39;s construction manager, the Scottish union GMB expressed its concerns that McVitie&#39;s &quot;will not deliver on its promises to finance and modernize production lines.&quot;
GMB chief organizer Drew Duffy added: “The fact that we have not received clear answers from the site manager regarding the needs of the company and the future plan for investment in Tollcross is of great concern to our members.
Generations of many families have worked here and the workforce is mostly drawn from the local community and the Glasgow area, where working in the local factory is a critical pillar of decent employment in an area of high unemployment and social exclusion.
From a work, pay and benefit perspective - and despite the prospect of Brexit, the rising cost of living and falling slow manufacturing - Glasgow East desperately needs a thriving manufacturer like McVitie&#39;s.&quot;
A spokeswoman for Pladis said: “Construction manager Tollcross only received the letter from GMB yesterday and the company will issue a statement as soon as possible as we value the continued commitment to staff and union representatives.
A regular meeting with GMB staff and representatives at Tollcross was held two months ago and many issues were openly discussed at this meeting.
We have discussed with employees that, as with all companies operating in extremely competitive and uncertain economic conditions, we evaluate our operations on a regular basis, which applies to all of our operations, so that we can continue to compete successfully with others.
She added: “We have invested £5 million in the Tollcross area in recent years, particularly in production lines and operational efficiencies.
We greatly value the heritage of Tollcross and the locality and any changes to the operation of the factory here will be communicated to staff and union representatives immediately.&quot;
